Certainly! Below is a C++ code snippet that defines a function `convertToFormalTone` which takes two arguments: the original sentence and a reference to the modified sentence. The function replaces the original sentence with a more formal one and returns the modified sentence.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string convertToFormalTone(const std::string& original, std::string& modified) {
    // Define the formal version of the sentence
    const std::string formalVersion = "I have been assigned to complete the task at hand";

    // Check if the input sentence matches the expected original sentence
    if (original == "I was requested to accomplish the task") {
        // Update the modified sentence
        modified = formalVersion;
    } else {
        // If the sentence doesn't match, retain the original sentence
        modified = original;
    }

    // Return the modified sentence
    return modified;
}

int main() {
    std::string originalSentence = "I was requested to accomplish the task";
    std::string modifiedSentence;

    std::string result = convertToFormalTone(originalSentence, modifiedSentence);

    std::cout << "Original Sentence: " << originalSentence << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Modified Sentence: " << result << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation:
- The function `convertToFormalTone` takes the original sentence as input and a reference to the `modified` sentence.
- It checks if the original sentence matches "I was requested to accomplish the task".
- If it matches, it sets the `modified` sentence to "I have been assigned to complete the task at hand".
- If it doesn't match, it leaves the `modified` sentence unchanged.
- The function returns the `modified` sentence, which is printed in the `main` function.
